
# Phase 4 - Findings

## Key Observations

- IAM activity provides high-value visibility into access and privilege changes
- Role assumption represents a critical event that may indicate privilege escalation or lateral movement
- Failed API calls provide strong detection signals for unauthorized behavior
- Identity enumeration is a common early-stage activity in cloud environments

## Security Implications

- Monitoring IAM activity is essential for detecting privilege misuse
- Role-based access introduces complexity that must be carefully monitored
- Failed actions can indicate attempted abuse even when access is denied

## Limitations

- Log ingestion was performed manually rather than in real time
- Detection logic relies on query-based analysis rather than automated alerting

## Improvements

- Automate ingestion from S3 into Splunk
- Implement real-time alerts for high-risk IAM events
- Correlate multiple event types to identify complex attack patterns

## Conclusion

This project demonstrates how AWS IAM activity can be analyzed using CloudTrail and Splunk to identify potential security-relevant behavior.

It highlights the importance of identity-focused monitoring in cloud security.
